1) What is Object Class in Java?
-->In Java, the Object Class (java.lang.Object) is the root of the entire class hierarchy. Every class in Java, whether built-in
    or user-defined, implicitly or explicitly extends the Object class, making it the ultimate superclass of all objects.

2) What is the superclass of all Java classes?
-->The superclass of all classes in Java is the Object class, which belongs to the java.lang package.
    Every class in Java, except for the Object class itself, implicitly inherits from it either directly or indirectly.

3) Is it necessary to extend Object class explicitly?
-->No, it is not necessary to explicitly extend the Object class. 
    In Java, every class you create automatically and implicitly inherits from java.lang.Object if you do not specify a different superclass. 

    Key Reasons Why Explicit Extension is Unnecessary:
    Implicit Inheritance: If you declare a class as public class MyClass {}, the Java compiler automatically treats it
    as public class MyClass extends Object {}.
    Indirect Inheritance: If your class extends another class (e.g., class B extends A), it still inherits from Object indirectly
    because A either extends Object directly or through its own parent hierarchy.
    Access to Core Methods: Because of this built-in inheritance, all classes automatically have access to essential methods
    defined in the Object class, such as:
    toString(): Returns a string representation of the object.
    equals(Object obj): Indicates whether some other object is "equal to" this one.
    hashCode(): Returns a hash code value for the object.
    getClass(): Returns the runtime class of the object.
    clone(), notify(), notifyAll(), and wait(). 


4) How many methods does the Object class have?
-->In Java, the Object class contains a total of 11 methods. These methods are automatically inherited by every other class in Java. 
    
    The methods can be categorized by their primary function: 
    Object Comparison & Identity
      equals(Object obj): Checks if another object is "equal to" the current one.
      hashCode(): Returns a numeric hash code value for the object, primarily used in hash-based collections like HashMap.
      getClass(): Returns the runtime class of the object. 

    Object Representation & Lifecycle
      toString(): Returns a string representation of the object.
      clone(): Creates and returns a copy of the object (requires the class to implement the Cloneable interface).
      finalize(): (Deprecated) Called by the garbage collector before an object is destroyed. 
      
    Thread Synchronization
    These five methods (including three overloads of wait) are used for inter-thread communication: 
      notify(): Wakes up a single thread waiting on the object's monitor.
      notifyAll(): Wakes up all threads waiting on the object's monitor.
      wait(): Causes the current thread to wait until notified.
      wait(long timeoutMillis): Wait with a specific timeout in milliseconds.
      wait(long timeoutMillis, int nanos): Wait with a specific timeout in milliseconds and nanoseconds. 


5) Can we override methods of the Object class?
-->Yes, we can override certain methods of the Object class in Java. Since every class in Java implicitly inherits from java.lang.Object, any non-final, non-static method can be redefined in a subclass to provide specific behavior. 

    Overridable Methods
    The following methods are commonly overridden to provide meaningful implementations for custom classes:
    toString(): By default, this returns a string consisting of the class name and the object's hash code. It is often overridden to return a readable representation of the object's state.
    equals(Object obj): Used to define "logical equality" (comparing values) instead of "reference equality" (comparing memory addresses).
    hashCode(): If equals() is overridden, hashCode() must also be overridden to maintain the contract that equal objects must have the same hash code.
    clone(): Overridden (and typically made public) to allow creating a field-for-field copy of an object. The class must also implement the Cloneable interface.
    finalize(): Used for cleanup before garbage collection, though it is now deprecated and generally discouraged in favor of AutoCloseable. 
    
    Non-Overridable (Final) Methods
    Several methods in the Object class are marked as final and cannot be overridden by any subclass: 
    getClass()
    notify()
    notifyAll()
    wait() (all versions)


6) Which methods are declared as final in the Object class?
-->The java.lang.Object class declares several methods as final to prevent subclasses from overriding their core behavior,
    which is critical for the stability of the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). 

    The final methods in the Object class include getClass(), which returns the runtime class of an object, and synchronization methods notify(),
        notifyAll(), and all three overloaded forms of wait(). These methods cannot be overridden by subclasses. 
    
    Conversely, methods such as equals(), hashCode(), toString(), clone(), and finalize() are not final and can be overridden.


7) What is the difference between == and equals()?
-->The main difference is that == is an operator that compares memory references (if two references point to the same object) or primitive values. In contrast, .equals() is a method that compares the actual content or state of two objects for logical equality. == cannot be overridden, whereas equals() can be. 
   
    Key Differences:
    Type: == is a binary operator, while equals() is a method defined in the Object class.
    Behavior: == checks for reference equality (address in memory). .equals() checks for value equality (content).
    Usage: == can be used for both primitives (like int, char) and objects. .equals() can only be used for objects.
    Customization: You cannot change how == works. You can override the .equals() method to define what equality means for your custom objects.
    Null Safety: == handles null safely (e.g., obj == null). Calling a.equals(b) will throw a NullPointerException if a is null.

8) Why should we override hashCode() when we override equals()?
-->You must override hashCode() when overriding equals() to ensure objects behave correctly in hash-based collections
    like HashSet or HashMap. If equals() says two objects are the same, their hashCode() must return the same integer; otherwise, the
    collection will fail to locate or identify duplicates, leading to bugs. 

Simple Explanation:
The Problem: equals() determines if two objects are logically equal (e.g., same ID). By default, hashCode() produces a number based on
          the object's memory address. If you only change equals(), two identical objects will still have different memory-based hash codes.
    The Consequence: When you put these objects in a HashMap, it uses the hash code to find the object's "bucket." If the hash codes are
        different, the HashMap puts them in different buckets, meaning equals() is never called to see they are actually the same. Result: You get duplicate objects.
    The Solution: Overriding hashCode() ensures that equal objects generate the same numerical "key," placing them in the same bucket and allowing equals() to work properly

    You must override hashCode() when overriding equals() to maintain the general contract for hashCode(), which states that equal objects must
    have equal hash codes. Failing to do so violates this contract, breaking hash-based collections like HashSet, HashMap, and Hashtable. 

    Key Reasons to Override Both:
    Hash-Based Collection Integrity: HashMap and HashSet use the hashCode() value to determine where to store an object (the bucket).
    If two objects are equal according to equals(), but have different hashCode() values, a map may store them in different buckets.

    Locating Objects: When retrieving an object from a HashMap, the map first uses the hash code to find the correct bucket.
      If the hash codes are different, the HashMap will not find the object, even if equals() would return true.

    Contractual Requirement: According to Java documentation, if a.equals(b) is true, then a.hashCode() must equal b.hashCode().

    Performance: While not required, returning distinct hash codes for unequal objects improves the performance of hash tables



9) What is the default implementation of toString()?
-->In Java, the default implementation of toString() (defined in the Object class) returns a string consisting of the class name, the '@' sign, and the unsigned hexadecimal representation of the object's hash code. It follows the format: getClass().getName() + '@' + Integer.toHexString(hashCode()). 
  
    Key Aspects of Default toString():
    Purpose: Provides a unique identifier for objects when not overridden.
    Example Output: com.example.MyClass@1a2b3c4d.
    Inheritance: Every class in Java inherits this implementation from java.lang.Object.
    Override: It is standard practice to override this method to provide human-readable, meaningful information about the object's state.
    Usage: It is automatically invoked when passing an object to System.out.println() or concatenating it with a string.

